> **[Title]** Predicting Lassa Fever Outbreaks Across Distinct Ecological Zones in Nigeria:
> An 8-Year Spatiotemporal Analysis Using Machine Learning and Time-Lagged Climate Drivers (2018–2025)
>
> **Authors:** Ayokunle John Tadema
>
> **Journal:** [Journal Name] | **Status:** Under Review
>
> **Manuscript DOI / Preprint:** ` `

This repository contains all analysis code, figure-generation scripts, and result tables that directly support the findings reported in the manuscript. Every figure and table in the paper can be reproduced by running the pipeline described below.

---

## 📁 Repository Structure

```
lassa-fever-ml-nigeria/
│
├── src/
│   ├── 01_data_integration.py        # Section 1–2:  Data loading, merging & lag imputation
│   ├── 02_descriptive_stats.py       # Section 3:    Descriptive statistics & climate summary
│   ├── 03_exploratory_figures.py     # Section 4–5:  Epidemic curves, trends, STL decomposition
│   ├── 04_correlation_analysis.py    # Section 6:    Spearman lagged cross-correlation
│   ├── 05_glm_regression.py          # Section 7:    Negative binomial GLM + IRR forest plot
│   ├── 06_ml_models.py               # Section 8:    Random Forest + LightGBM modelling
│   ├── 07_shap_analysis.py           # Section 9:    SHAP interpretability analysis
│   ├── 08_uncertainty.py             # Section 10:   Bootstrap confidence intervals
│   ├── 09_granger_causality.py       # Section 11:   Granger causality tests
│   ├── 10_sarima_baseline.py         # Section 12:   SARIMA baseline model
│   ├── 11_outbreak_detection.py      # Section 13:   Early warning system
│   ├── 12_tables_export.py           # Section 14:   Manuscript tables
│   ├── 13_elevation_sensitivity.py   # Section 15:   Elevation sensitivity analysis
│   └── utils.py                      # Shared helpers: metrics, colours, savefig
│
├── lassa_analysis_complete.py        # ← Single-file pipeline (run this for full reproduction)
│
├── notebooks/
│   └── exploratory_analysis.ipynb   # Interactive Jupyter/Colab notebook version
│
├── data/
│   ├── README_data.md               # Data sources, variables, access instructions
│   ├── Lassa_climate_features_engineered.csv   # [NOT INCLUDED — see data/README_data.md]
│   └── Cases_rainfal_data.csv                  # [NOT INCLUDED — see data/README_data.md]
│
├── figures/                         # All generated figures (300 DPI PNG)
│   └── [auto-generated on run]
│
├── results/                         # All generated tables (CSV)
│   └── [auto-generated on run]
│
├── requirements.txt                 # Python package dependencies
├── environment.yml                  # Conda environment specification
├── LICENSE                          # MIT License
└── README.md                        # This file
```

---

## 🚀 Quick Start

### Option 1 — Google Colab (Recommended)

Click the badge below to open the full pipeline in Google Colab:

[![Open in Colab](https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg)](https://colab.research.google.com/github/tadema00/lassa-fever-ml-nigeria/blob/main/notebooks/exploratory_analysis.ipynb)

Then upload your two data files when prompted:
- `Lassa_climate_features_engineered.csv`
- `Cases_rainfal_data.csv`

### Option 2 — Local Installation

```bash
# 1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/tadema00/lassa-fever-ml-nigeria.git
cd lassa-fever-ml-nigeria

# 2. Create and activate environment
conda env create -f environment.yml
conda activate lassa-ml

# OR with pip
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 3. Place your data files in the data/ folder
cp /path/to/Lassa_climate_features_engineered.csv data/
cp /path/to/Cases_rainfal_data.csv data/

# 4. Run the full pipeline
python lassa_analysis_complete.py
```

All figures will be saved to `figures/` and all tables to `results/`.

---

## 📊 Analysis Pipeline Overview

| Section | Script | Description | Outputs |
|---------|--------|-------------|---------|
| 1–2 | `01_data_integration.py` | Load, merge & impute lag features | `Lassa_Final_Merged_Dataset.csv` |
| 3 | `02_descriptive_stats.py` | Case burden & climate summaries | Table 1 |
| 4–5 | `03_exploratory_figures.py` | Epidemic curves, heatmaps, STL | Figs 1–6 |
| 6 | `04_correlation_analysis.py` | Spearman lag–response analysis | Figs 7–8, Table 2 |
| 7 | `05_glm_regression.py` | Negative binomial GLM, IRR forest plot | Fig 9, Table NB |
| 8 | `06_ml_models.py` | RF + LightGBM, 5-fold time-series CV | Figs 10–11, Table 3 |
| 9 | `07_shap_analysis.py` | Global & state-stratified SHAP, PDP, waterfall | Figs 12a–12f |
| 10 | `08_uncertainty.py` | Bootstrap 95% CI (B=500) | Fig 13, Table 4 |
| 11 | `09_granger_causality.py` | Granger temporal precedence tests | Fig 14, Table 5 |
| 12 | `10_sarima_baseline.py` | SARIMA AIC grid search, RF vs SARIMA | Figs 15–16, Table 6 |
| 13 | `11_outbreak_detection.py` | Rolling early warning system | Fig 17, Table 7 |
| 14 | `12_tables_export.py` | Consolidated manuscript tables | Table 8 |
| 15 | `13_elevation_sensitivity.py` | Elevation as geographic proxy — sensitivity | Fig 18 |

---

## 📦 Dependencies

| Package | Version | Purpose |
|---------|---------|---------|
| `pandas` | ≥1.5 | Data manipulation |
| `numpy` | ≥1.23 | Numerical computation |
| `matplotlib` | ≥3.6 | Figure generation |
| `seaborn` | ≥0.12 | Statistical visualisation |
| `scikit-learn` | ≥1.2 | Random Forest, metrics, CV |
| `statsmodels` | ≥0.14 | SARIMA, NB GLM, STL, Granger |
| `scipy` | ≥1.10 | Spearman correlation, statistics |
| `shap` | ≥0.43 | SHAP interpretability |
| `lightgbm` | ≥4.0 | Gradient boosting (optional) |

Install all at once:
```bash
pip install pandas numpy matplotlib seaborn scikit-learn statsmodels scipy shap lightgbm
```

